<p>The <b>Daman and Diu Portuguese</b> or <b>Daman and Diu Indo-Portuguese</b>, known to its speakers as <i><b>Língua da Casa</b></i> (<a href="/wiki/Portuguese_language" title="Portuguese language">Portuguese</a> for "Home language"), is a <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_language" title="Portuguese language">Portuguese</a>-based <a href="/wiki/Creole_language" title="Creole language">creole</a> spoken in <a href="/wiki/Daman_and_Diu" title="Daman and Diu">Daman and Diu</a>. Before the Indian annexation of the territory, the Daman creole went through a profound <a href="/wiki/Decreolization" title="Decreolization">decreolization</a> by Standard Portuguese of <a href="/wiki/Goa" title="Goa">Goa</a>, a phenomenon whereby the Indo-Portuguese creole reconverged with Standard Portuguese.</p>
<p></p>
